ilding contains four one-ton cylinders of chlorine. Two, one-ton containers are connected to the system and the other two serve as backup. The chlorine cylinders are equipped with manual shutoff valves in the event of an emergency, and an alarm activates at the occurrence of released chlorine. Personnel oversee the facility 24-hours a day, including daily inspections of the chlorine building. The facility houses emergency air and power supply. Self-Contained-Breathing-Apparatus (SCBA) storage are stored on site. 

The offsite consequence analysis for the Wastewater Treatment Plant includes consideration of two release scenarios for each parameter of concern (chlorine): 
1. A Worst-Case Release
2. An Alternative Scenario
The following key elements outline the accidental release prevention program for the Weslaco Wastewater Treatment Plant:

$    High level of training of the operators;

$    Preventive maintenance program;

$    Use of state of the art process and safety equipment;

$    Use of accurate and effective operating procedures, written with the participation of the operators;

$    Performance of a hazard review of equipment and procedures;

$    Implementation of an audit and inspection program.

Chemical specific prevention steps include operator use of available Self-Contained-Breathing-Apparatus (SCBA) during connection/disconnection of the chemical supply, awareness of the hazardous and toxic properties of chlorine and the presence of a chemical detector.  An Agreement with Chemical Response & Remediation Contractors, Inc.(CRRC) a local hazardous material team has been made for assistance with emergency response.

No accidental releases of chlorine have occurred at the site in the past five years.

